font></font></font></font></center><font color=3D"000000"><font size=3D"2">=
<font size=3D"3"><font color=3D"000099">
Yes, information concerning aphelion, perihelion and average distance is al=
so displayed, but if you are not dealing with planetary orbits, you can jus=
t ignore these.<p>
This ellipse calculator comes in handy for astronomical calculations.<br>
The asteroid Eros has an orbital eccentricity of .223 and an average distan=
ce from the Sun of 1.458 astronomical units.<br>
Click on the "Average Distance and Eccentricity" button, enter these number=
s, click "CALCULATE" then you will see its perihelion and aphelion distance=
s along with its perimeter, area, foci distance and so on.
<font size=3D"6"><font color=3D"CC0000">
</font></font></p><center><font size=3D"6"><font color=3D"CC0000">* * * * *=
 * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *<=
/font></font></center><font size=3D"6"><font color=3D"CC0000">

<p><font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"3">
It seems in geometry that the ellipse is the "forgotten stepbrother" of the=
 circle even though the ellipse is far more interesting. =20
First some definitions.</font></font></p><p><font color=3D"000099"><font si=
ze=3D"3">

</font></font></p><p><font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"3">
</font></font></p><center><font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"3"><img src=
=3D"https://www.1728.org/ellps2.png"></font></font></center><font color=3D"=
000099"><font size=3D"3">

An<font color=3D"#CC0000"> ellipse
<font color=3D"#000099">is the locus of points the sum of whose distances=
=20
from two fixed points, called foci, is a constant.<br>
Line AB is the <font color=3D"#CC0000">Major Axis<font color=3D"#000099"> (=
also called Long Axis or Line of Apsides).<br>
Lines AO and OB are the <font color=3D"#CC0000">Semi-Major axes <font color=
=3D"000099">which also equals Line a. <br>
<font color=3D"#000099">Line CD is the <font color=3D"#CC0000">Minor Axis<f=
ont color=3D"#000099"> and is the perpendicular bisector of the Major Axis.=
<br>
Lines OC and OD are the <font color=3D"#CC0000">Semi-Minor axes <font color=
=3D"000099">which also equals Line b.<br>
<font color=3D"CC0000">Points f<sub>1</sub> and f<sub>2</sub><font color=3D=
"000099"> are the <font color=3D"#CC0000">

foci <font color=3D"#000099"> of the ellipse.<br>

Points A and B are called <font color=3D"#CC0000">apses.<font color=3D"#000=
099"><br>
Johannes Kepler's First Law states that the planets move in elliptical orbi=
ts with the Sun located at one of the foci.<br>
If we were dealing with <font color=3D"#CC0000">planetary orbits <font colo=
r=3D"#000099">and we were to say the Sun were at f<sub>1</sub> then:<br>
Line A f1 would be the <font color=3D"#CC0000">perihelion distance<font col=
or=3D"#000099"><br>=20
Line f1 B would be the <font color=3D"#CC0000">aphelion distance<font color=
=3D"#000099"> and<br>
Line AO is the planet's <font color=3D"#CC0000">average (or mean) distance =
<font color=3D"#000099"> and would be one half of the major axis.<p>


For ellipse <font color=3D"#CC0000">eccentricity<font color=3D"#000099"> fo=
rmulas, see the graphic at the top of the page.<br>
<!-- <CENTER>
<img src=3D"ellipse2.gif">
</CENTER>-->

</font></font></p><p><font color=3D"#CC0000"><font color=3D"#000099">
As the eccentricity value goes from 0 to 1, the=20
ellipse goes from circular to highly elongated.</font></font></p><p><font c=
olor=3D"#CC0000"><font color=3D"#000099">
The table below shows the formulas for calculating ellipse perimeter, ellip=
se aspect ratio and ellipse area.<br>
=20
</font></font></p><center><font color=3D"#CC0000"><font color=3D"#000099"><=
img src=3D"https://www.1728.org/elpsar1.png">


</font></font></center><font color=3D"#CC0000"><font color=3D"#000099">

<font color=3D"#000099"><p><font size=3D"3">
</font></p><p><font size=3D"3">
Surprisingly, unlike the calculation of a circle's perimeter, calculating t=
he cirumference of an ellipse is much more complicated and requires=20
a rather complex formula.  In fact, there is <i>no</i> formula that will pr=
ecisely generate an ellipse's circumference.  The most accurate=20
equation for an ellipse's circumference was found by Indian mathematician <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramanujan">
Srinivasa Ramanujan</a> (1887-1920) (see the above graphic for the formula)=
 and it is this formula that is used in the calculator. =20
</font></p><p><font size=3D"3">
The eccentricity of an ellipse is <i>not</i> such a good indicator=20
of its shape.  For example, Pluto has one of the most=20
eccentric orbits in the solar system with an eccentricity value of .245.  T=
his might=20
create the impression that the orbit is somewhat flattened.  Actually,=20
by using the calculator, we see that the minor to major axis ratio is=20
about .97 which is practically circular.</font></p><p><font size=3D"3">
We drew a graphic (see below) to show the shape of an ellipse over a wide r=
ange of eccentricities.  As you can see, even at an eccentricity of .3 an e=
llipse still appears as if it is circular, and this is an eccentricity that=
 is even greater than Pluto's.   =20
</font></p><center><font size=3D"3"><img src=3D"https://www.1728.org/ellps.=
png"></font></center><font size=3D"3">

<p><br>
</p><hr size=3D"3" noshade=3D"" width=3D"85%" color=3D"000000">
<center><font color=3D"#CC0000"><font size=3D"5">
<u>Drawing Ellipses</u></font></font></center><font color=3D"#CC0000"><font=
 size=3D"5">
<font color=3D"000099"><font size=3D"3"><p>
The traditional way to draw an ellipse is to make a loop of string or=20
thread, place two thumbtacks in a sheet of paper, put the loop over the=20
thumbtacks and then with a pen, keeping the loop tight at all times, go=20
completely around the thumbtacks.</p><p>
Referring to the ellipse at the top of the page, the triangle C f1 f2=20
would represent the loop of string, the thumbtacks would be at f1 and f2=20
and the pen would start out at point C.</p><p>

=20
This works fine, except you are not exactly sure of what the ellipse is
going to look like (how eccentric, minor to major axis ratio, etc.). =20
Therefore this calculator will determine how far apart the thumbtacks have=
=20
to be for a required eccentricity.
=20
</p><center>
<form name=3D"input3">
<!-- THIS IS INPUT BOX 1-->
<font size=3D"3">
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N11" value=3D"String Loop=3D" size=3D"15">
<!-- THIS IS INPUT BOX 2-->
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N12" size=3D"15">
=20
<br>

<!-- THIS IS INPUT BOX 3-->
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N13" value=3D"Eccentricity=3D" size=3D"15">
<!-- THIS IS INPUT BOX 4-->
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N14" size=3D"15">
<br>

<!-- THIS IS THE ENTER BUTTON -->
<input type=3D"button" value=3D"E  N  T  E  R" size=3D" 20" ;=3D"" return=
=3D"" true=3D"">
=20
<br>
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N15" value=3D"Thumbtack Distance=3D" size=3D"1=
5">
<!-- THIS IS INPUT BOX 3-->
<input type=3D"text" name=3D"N16" size=3D"15">
=20
=20

</font></form></center><font size=3D"3">
<p>
<u>Example:</u> If you make a loop of string 10 inches long, and want an=20
ellipse with an eccentricity of .5, enter these figures in the calculator=
=20
and your answer will be a thumbtack distance of 6.66666 inches.

</p><p></p><p><br>
</p><hr size=3D"3" noshade=3D"" width=3D"65%" color=3D"000099">
<font color=3D"#CC0000">

<center><u>
Other Ellipse Properties
</u></center>
<font color=3D"#000099">
<p>
Referring to the ellipse diagram at the top of the page, let us suppose=20
that it is a pool table and imagine that f1 and f2 are spots on the table. =
=20
If you were to shoot the ball from anyplace over=20
spot f1, the ball would then go over spot f2, then f1 and so on.<br>If you=
=20
shot the ball through line Af1, the ball would go through line f2B and=20
no matter how many times it is deflected, the ball will <i>never</i> cross=
=20
line f1f2.  <br>
=20
Conversely, if you were to shoot the ball anywhere through=20
f1f2, it will continue to cross line f1f2 with each deflection and will=20
<i> never</i> travel through Lines Af1 or f2B.<br>

If we were talking about rays of light and the inside of the ellipse were=
=20
reflective, the same behavior would be exhibited by the light, just as in t=
he=20
pool table example.</p><p>
You may have heard of "whispering galleries" in which one person stands=20
in a certain spot and whispers while another person stands at another spot=
=20
and can hear the other person perfectly.  How does this work?  The gallery=
=20
walls are elliptical in shape, and so if one person stands at f1, the sound=
=20
waves will be directed through f2, where the other person will be standing.=
 =20
One of the chambers in the US House of Representatives is shaped this way. =
</p><p>
This web page has only explored the tip of the "ellipse iceberg" so to spea=
k. =20
For example, the ellipse can also be defined as the locus of points whose=
=20
distance ratio from one focus to a straight line (called a directrix) is=20
equal to the eccentricity of the ellipse.  But you probably knew that right=
? =20
=20
<br>
Also, we barely discussed the mathematical properties of the ellipse such=
=20
as ellipse equations.  Nor did we discuss the fact that the ellipse is=20
one of the four conic sections.  (See?  the fun never ends.)<br>
To find out more about ellipses, use your favorite search engine.  No=20
doubt you will find <i>loads</i> of information.  Good luck with your=20
elliptical internet explorations.=20

</p><hr size=3D"3" noshade=3D"" width=3D"75%" color=3D"000099">

